SIMPLE: espy
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Espy
<hw>Es*py"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Espied</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Espying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF. <ets>espier</ets>, F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧pier</ets>, from OHG. <ets>speh<?/n</ets> to watch, spy, G.
<ets>sp⟦aum⟧hen</ets>; akin to L. <ets>specere</ets> to look,
<ets>species</ets> sight, shape, appearance, kind. See <er>Spice</er>,
<er>Spy</er>, and cf. <er>Espionage</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
catch sight of; to perceive with the eyes; to discover, as a distant
object partly concealed, or not obvious to notice; to see at a glance;
to discern unexpectedly; to spy; <as>as, to <ex>espy</ex> land; to
<ex>espy</ex> a man in a crowd.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As one of them opened his sack to give his ass provender in the
inn, . . . he <qex>espied</qex> his money.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. xlii.
27.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A goodly vessel did I then <qex>espy</qex>⟦br⟧
Come like a giant from a haven broad.</q>
<rj><qau>Wordsworth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To inspect narrowly; to examine and keep watch upon;
to watch; to observe.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He sends angels to <qex>espy</qex> us in all our ways.</q>
<rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To discern; discover; detect; descry;
spy.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Espy</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Espy
<hw>Es*py"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To look or search narrowly; to
look about; to watch; to take notice; to spy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Stand by the way, and <qex>espy</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. xlviii.
19.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Espy</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Espy
<hw>Es*py"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Espies</plw>
<pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OF. <ets>espie</ets>. See <er>Espy</er>, v.,
<er>Spy</er>.]</ety> <def>A spy; a scout.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Huloet.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

